[One of the causes of past mass mortalities of saiga antelopes (known in the former USSR as "Saigak") in Kazakhstan was foot-mouth-disease (FMD). During a major outbreak in the late 1960's, the disease reportedly spread along the north-south annual migration route of the animals, at that time counting several hundred thousands. Among the signs observed was the loss of horns and hooves, and considerable mortality (Ref 1). Experimental infection with FMDV caused up to 75 percent mortality; up to 10 percent of the free-living population reportedly died during natural outbreaks (Ref 2).

The description above of 1500 animals found dead along the shores of Lake Tengiz, is reminiscent of the situation observed in northern Israel in 1985, when -- during a mass FMD-O epizootic killing more than 2000 _Gazella gazellae_ antelopes (more than 60 percent of the population), most dying animals were observed along water sources in a state of dehydration (unable to drink). Laboratory investigations revealed (secondary) pneumonia with _Pasteurella_ in several cases. Sudden death of ruminants, due to cardiac changes caused by FMD virus, is a long-known phenomenon.

FMDV serotype A has reportedly been identified earlier this year (2013) in cattle in East Kazakhstan. FMD deserves to be included among the infectious and non-infectious agents addressed by the investigators in the affected saigak. Results will be appreciated.

References
----------
1. Kindyakov VI, Nagumanov FM, Balgangayev EC, et al (1970): Epizootiological significance of wild even-toed ungulates in the case of foot and mouth disease. Veterinariya 47, 52-3.
2. Sokolov VE, Zhirnov LV (Eds.), 1998: Saigak. Filogeniya, Sistematika, Ekologiya, Okhrana I Ispozovaniye [The Saiga Antelope. Phylogeny, Systematics, Conservation and Land Use]. Moscow. - Mod.AS

Maps of Kazakhstan can be seen at http://www.ezilon.com/maps/images/asia/political-map-of-Kazakhstan.gif and http://healthmap.org/r/1AhF. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
